4 Assumptions for Multiple Regression Models

Exercise

Run a regression model called m1 predicting Variable1 from Variable2 and Variable3.


Refer to week 4 workshop for parametric assumptions. We will talk about some assumptions that are specific to linear regression models today.

4.1 Linearity and Homoscedasticity

Residual vs predicted plot is commonly used to examine linearity and homoscedasticity.

Two parts of this plot:

  • Linearity - a straight red line.
  • Homoscedasticity - scores should be equally spread around the red line
plot(m1, 1)

Interpreting R Plot

Assumptions are met when the red line is flat and horizontal (linearity) and the data points are equally and randomly spread (homoscedasticity).


Alternatively you can use the scale-location plot to examine homoscedasticity. It plots the square rooted standardized residual vs. predicted values.

plot(m1, 3)

Interpreting R Plot

Assumption is met when the data points data points are equally and randomly spread.

4.2 Normality of Residuals

Normality of Residuals can be examined by plotting the standardised residuals using a QQ plot.

plot(m1, 2)

Interpreting R Plot

Assumption is met when the data points observations fall along the diagonal straight line.

4.3 Multicollinearity

Several ways to check for multicollinearity:

  • Correlation Matrix
  • Variance Inflation Factors (VIF)

4.3.1 Correlation Matrix

We can use the cor() and corrplot() functions to create a plot of a correlation matrix.

corrplot(cor(d[, .(Variable1, Variable2, Variable3)]), method = "number")

Interpreting R Plot

Multicollinearity is indicated when the correlation between two (predictor) variables is below -0.9 or above +0.9

4.3.2 Variance Inflation Factors

We can use the ols_vif_tol() function from the olsrr package to calculate the Tolerance and the Variance Inflation Factor values.

ols_vif_tol(m1)
##   Variables Tolerance   VIF
## 1 Variable2    0.9138 1.094
## 2 Variable3    0.9138 1.094

Interpreting R Output

Multicollinearity may be indicated when VIF > 10.

5 Multiple Regression with Continuous and Categorical Predictors

5.1 Dummy Coding - Categorical/Factor variables

Factor variables in R are used to represent categorical data. Factors store data as integer values (i.e., levels) with a corresponding set of character values (i.e., labels) to use when the factor is displayed. While factors look like character vectors, they are actually integers. For example, when we make the sex variable a factor variable, by setting male = 0 and female = 1, sex variable will be displayed as male/female in R. However, when it is entered into a regression model, R will help us do dummy coding. Dummy coding is helpful as you can examine categorical variable in a regression model. That’s why we usually convert categorical data into factors.

Let’s try this on the Sex variable. First, take a look at how it is currently coded using the table() function.

class(d$Sex)
## [1] "integer"
table(d$Sex)
## 
##   0   1 
##  93 287

We create a factor using the factor() function.

d[, Sex := factor(
  Sex,
  levels = c(0,1),
  labels = c("Male", "Female"))]

See how it is now after being recoded.

class(d$Sex)
## [1] "factor"
table(d$Sex)
## 
##   Male Female 
##     93    287

In the datset, we can see that the labels, rather than levels, are displayed.

# View(d)

You Try It

Convert the BornAUS variable into a factor. You can keep the name, or give it a new name.

5.2 Create Categorical Variables from Continuous Variables

As an example, I assigned marks to participants by creating a variable called Mark in the dataset d which has random values from 1 to 100. This variable is numeric data.

d[, Mark := rep(sample(0:100), length.out = nrow(d))]

We can create a new categorical variable called Grade. that group these people according to their marks using the cut() function.

d[, Grade := cut(Mark,
                 breaks = c(-Inf, 49.99, 59.99, 69.99, 79.99, Inf),
                 labels = c("N", "P", "C", "D", "HD"))]
table(d$Grade)
## 
##   N   P   C   D  HD 
## 188  39  37  39  77

5.3 Changing the reference level of a factor

Factors in R come in two varieties: ordered (e.g., small, medium, large) and unordered (e.g., rose, daisy, lavender). For dummy variables, it is often helpful to set a reference level or “baseline” value. For example, consider our categorical predictor variable “Sex” with levels “Male” and “Female”. If “Male” is our reference, the model outout for regression will give us a coefficient for “Female”, which can be interpreted as the difference in the outcome between Female and Male.

When there are more than two levels, this reference level becomes more useful for interpretation. For example, we may have a specific group that we want to compare against the other groups. Let’s take a look at the Alcohol Risk Category variable in the PSY3062 dataset.

class(d$AUDITCat)
## [1] "character"

Since it is “character” variable, not a integer variable as “Sex”, we can’t assign levels/labels to it. We will go head to convert it to a factor.

d$AUDITCat <- as.factor(d$AUDITCat)
str(d$AUDITCat)
##  Factor w/ 3 levels "Abstainer","At Risk",..: 3 3 3 3 3 3 2 1 3 3 ...

This works fine, but what if we want to compare all groups with the “At risk” group?

d[, AUDITCat := relevel(AUDITCat, ref = "At Risk")]
str(d$AUDITCat)
##  Factor w/ 3 levels "At Risk","Abstainer",..: 3 3 3 3 3 3 1 2 3 3 ...

5.4 Model

m2 <- lm(Variable1 ~ Variable2 + AUDITCat, data = d)
summary(m2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Variable1 ~ Variable2 + AUDITCat, data = d)

## Residual standard error: 4.23 on 376 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.0153, Adjusted R-squared:  0.00744 
## F-statistic: 1.95 on 3 and 376 DF,  p-value: 0.121

In the above output,

You can see that there is no row showing result for the At Risk group. This is because in the model, each dummy variable (Abstainer and Moderate, respectively) is compared with the reference group (At Risk). The coefficients tell us the difference in the outcome (Variable1) between the each group (dummy = 1) and the reference group (dummy = 0). These results are not significant, but if they are, we can write them up as below.

Sample Write-up for Dummy variables

A multiple regression model was used to examine whether Variable2 and Alcohol Risk predict Variable1. The results showed that, Abstainer had -0.81 lower Variable1 than the At Risk group [95% CI -2.33, 0.72], p = .298. The Moderate group also had lower Variable1 than the At Risk group (b = -1.05 [95% CI -2.43, 0.33], p = .136).

Notes. Results are not significant, this write-up is only for teaching purposes.
